			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Personally, most of my issue with beastlords comes from 3 simple things.
<br />

<br />
1. Pet heal.  They're part shaman, so I can deal with them having better heals... But they should be HoT based.  When was the last time you saw a shaman healing for 2100 with no focus and no AAs?
<br />

<br />
2. Slow.  10% isn't a large enough difference to make shamans more than buffbots.  SoE nerfs DOS (61%, extremely random, lands less due to lesser pet level) because it makes pets too powerful yet BST have a 65% innate slow?  Can someone with a beefier IQ than myself resolve this discrepancy for me please?  I believe I am confused.
<br />

<br />
3. Warder vs Mage elemental.  Elemental base stats are better.  But not by enough of a margin to merit the Bo6 vs Growl difference.  We're not refuting that beastlords are a class with a pet, but seriously Churizo...  You're contradicting yourself.  A beastlord's offensive strategy does not revolve around his warder.  You've noted numerous times that he's just a DoT, that high level well equipped beastlords tank far better.  Having a warder is a nice addition to your DPS, but a large amount of your power comes from your melee AAs and spells, not your warder.  Mages are not capable of healing themselves, so even if you do have uber gear, we're not going to be able to maintain our HP.  I have a L65 BST friend without DPoC that solos PoV easily for fun, and I have to bot a shaman or yo-yo kite to do it.  
<br />

<br />
I'm not into nerfing beastlords.  But if most of the other classes in the game can solo 10 aas a day with a casual investment of time, mages need to be brought into the fold.
<br />

<br />
Fin.<br />_________________<br />Dorai Darkspire, 65 Arch Convoker of Maelin Starpyre
