<br />

<br />
1. Pet heal.  They're part shaman, so I can deal with them having better heals... But they should be HoT based.  When was the last time you saw a shaman healing for 2100 with no focus and no AAs?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Pet only heal which can only be cast on the beastlord's warder.  Compare a beastlord's regular heal with that of a shaman...  But, if you had read any of my past posts, you would see that I am in favor of mages receiving a heal similar to that of a beastlords.  Both should be with a reduced cast time as well with no recast.  When I suggested that, several mages demanded that their heal be better than a beastlord's because they are the "premier" pet class.  That is bullshit.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">2. Slow.  10% isn't a large enough difference to make shamans more than buffbots.  SoE nerfs DOS (61%, extremely random, lands less due to lesser pet level) because it makes pets too powerful yet BST have a 65% innate slow?  Can someone with a beefier IQ than myself resolve this discrepancy for me please?  I believe I am confused.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The amount of difference between 65% and 75% isn't as easy as saying it's only 10 percent.  There is a large difference in the amount of slow.  Also, a shaman gets more typoes of slows.  The beastlord slow is very easily resisted.  I don't believe you factor in the different offensive styles of a beastlord vs a mage (that justifies the need for slows).  A mage needs a pet that can tank for a shorter amount of time than a beastlord does.  A mage is able to generate a far greater DPS, therefore the fights are shorter in duration.  For my average exp mob solo, it may take me 3 mins or so to kill the mob.  A mage will kill an exp mob in far less time.  Beastlords must be able to sustain the pet and him/herself during the time it takes to kill the mob.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">3. Warder vs Mage elemental.  Elemental base stats are better.  But not by enough of a margin to merit the Bo6 vs Growl difference.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
You are forgetting the mitigation bonuses that pets receive.  Mage earth pet's (main tanking pet for a mage) mitigation is more than that of a warder.  A mage's earth pet is a superior tank compared to a warder.  Yes, warders can tank though, but not as good.  It is at a level of difference which I am happy with.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">We're not refuting that beastlords are a class with a pet, but seriously Churizo...  You're contradicting yourself.  A beastlord's offensive strategy does not revolve around his warder.  You've noted numerous times that he's just a DoT, that high level well equipped beastlords tank far better.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
How is am I contradicting myself?  Pets have not scaled with content.  This is for mage and beastlord pets.  Both of the pets need to be reworked.  I have never asked for a warder that is equal in power to that of a mage pet.  I believe warders should be at about 80% of a mage pet.  They are currently at that level.  What I ask for is an across the board pet upgrade that keeps the same percentage base of difference.  
<br />

<br />
BTW, why is it so difficult for you to say "pet class" instead of a "class with a pet?"  That statement alone shows your bias.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Having a warder is a nice addition to your DPS, but a large amount of your power comes from your melee AAs and spells, not your warder.  Mages are not capable of healing themselves, so even if you do have uber gear, we're not going to be able to maintain our HP.  I have a L65 BST friend without DPoC that solos PoV easily for fun, and I have to bot a shaman or yo-yo kite to do it.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
A warder is an intergal part of a beastlord's combat effectiveness just as a mage + pet.  You do not rely on your pet any more or any less.  Without my pet, my ability to solo for exp is about nil and my group/raid effectiveness is diminished.  If you look at parses for a beastlord in raids, you will notice that a decently equipped beastlord + pet is putting out about 200 or so DPS (many times alot lower because of other duties), with pets accounting for about 30-40% of that DPS.  30-40% is not a minor amount.  With DPoC POV is soloable for a beastlord.  However, it is not easy as the mobs there hit hard and can have a nasty proc.  Unless kiting (which mages do there just as effectively) it is not an efficient solo spot for a DPoC equipped beastlord.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'm not into nerfing beastlords.  But if most of the other classes in the game can solo 10 aas a day with a casual investment of time, mages need to be brought into the fold.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
